# 4. Detailed Activity Breakdown

## 4.1 Application Discovery and Integration Assessment

### Objective

Establish a complete understanding of the CAN application scope, integration points, dependencies and changes required to incorporate CAN into the LEAP production platform.

### Activities

- Review the CAN functional scope and delivery backlog.
- Identify frontend, backend and orchestration components to be integrated.
- Review existing CAN code repositories and branch strategy.
- Identify shared libraries, common services and reusable components.
- Compare CAN components against the Investment reference implementation.
- Identify differences in coding conventions, frameworks and dependency versions.
- Map all application dependencies.
- Identify external API dependencies.
- Identify synchronous and asynchronous integration points.
- Identify data persistence and state management requirements.
- Identify configuration, secrets and environment-specific dependencies.
- Identify application changes that may affect existing Investment functionality.
- Identify technical debt and incomplete components before integration.
- Identify release sequencing constraints.
- Identify migration or compatibility requirements.
- Identify required application-level changes for Dev, Test, UAT and Production.
- Produce an initial integration risk register.

### Execution Approach

The activity is executed through repository reviews, specification reviews, technical workshops, architecture walkthroughs and dependency mapping sessions with the CAN delivery team.

### Deliverables

- Application Integration Assessment.
- Application Dependency Map.
- Component Inventory.
- Integration Risk Register.
- Initial Integration Backlog.
- Open Questions and Decision Log.

### Completion Criteria

- All major application components are inventoried.
- Critical integration dependencies are identified.
- High-risk compatibility issues are documented.
- Integration activities are converted into an actionable backlog.

